===Noun===
{{en-noun|~}}

# The behaviour of an [[adventurer]]; risk-taking. {{defdate|from 19th c.}}
#* '''1969''', {{w|Philip Roth}}, ''{{w|Portnoy's Complaint|Portnoy’s Complaint}}'', New York: Random House, p. 161,
#*: {{...}} she really hadn’t wanted me to think of her as given over ''wholly'' to sexual excess and '''adventurism''' {{...}}
#* '''1980''', {{w|Susan Sontag}}, “Fascinating Fascism” in ''{{w|Under the Sign of Saturn}}'', New York: Vintage, 1981, pp. 101-102,
#*: In pornographic literature, films, and gadgetry throughout the world {{...}} the {{w|Schutzstaffel|SS}} has become a [[referent]] of sexual '''adventurism'''.
# {{lb|en|politics}} The taking of excessive [[risk]]s by a government in their [[political]], [[economic]] or [[foreign]] affairs. {{defdate|from 20th c.}}
#* '''1993''', {{w|Ngũgĩ wa Thiong'o|Ngũgĩ wa Thiong’o}}, ''Moving the Centre: The Struggle for Cultural Freedom'', Nairobi: EAEP, Part I, Chapter 2, p. 22,
#*: Even where they were aware of the devastating effects of imperialism on the subject peoples, as in {{w|Joseph Conrad|Conrad}}’s description of the dying victims of colonial '''adventurism''' in ''{{w|Heart of Darkness}}'', they could not free themselves from the Eurocentric basis of their vision.
#* '''2002''', {{w|Colin Jones (historian)|Colin Jones}}, ''The Great Nation'', Penguin 2003, p. 133:
#*: The rejection of foreign '''adventurism''' derived partly from an awareness of the dynastic vulnerability of the Bourbon line, partly from the country's economic as well as its military fragility – and partly too from the increasingly evident limitations of France's traditional international allies.

